    <body><div type="letter">
      <p>Weddy 4 o'clock</p>
      <p>Dearest Old Crow. I have just been performing several visits of duty; &amp; where people were not at home, I performed for you also with cards. I really am quite perky &amp; proud of myself, for having been so proper &amp; dutiful a Bird. I do</p>
      <p>so hate making calls.</p>
      <p>I am continuing to improve in health &amp;c. It seems to be desirable for me to sing several hours a day; &amp; Hester recommends my endeavouring (as this is the case) to become quite an Artiste in that line, &amp; to study it dramatically as well as musically. It appears that I can at present endure nothing whatever that is sedentary; &amp; that the</p>
      <p>system necessary for my health is that of everything which can expand the lungs &amp; chest, &amp; also give vent to my strong dramatic tendencies, which certainly require some active scope; &amp; by studying music &amp; singing in the right way, this scope can be furnished without going on the Stage. I shall be able in time to sing Scenas with some one or two Artistes; &amp; in</p>
      <p>Scena singing, there is always action &amp; dramatic effect given, just as on the Stage; only without the bothers &amp; accompaniments of any of the Stage-adjuncts &amp; arrangements.--</p>
      <p>You would be proud of me, if ever I became a sort of Miss Kemble in my singing &amp; powers, &amp; I do not think it absolutely impossible. It is evident that for the present it is this</p>
      <p>line of study &amp; interest which is necessary for my health &amp; happiness; &amp; I have been consulting &amp; considering much on the plans best for me; &amp; feel that I am at last coming to some satisfactory conclusions.</p>
      <p>The dramatic line (by which pray mind that I in no way mean being on the Stage; I use the term in its widest &amp; most philosophical sense), is clearly the only one</p>
      <p>which diverts my Hysteria from all its mischievous &amp; irritating channels.--</p>
      <p>I have consulted much with Dr L--, who says my case is absolutely unique in much that he has lately become aware of more &amp; more completely, and that vents of an artificial kind for hysterical tendencies I must have; or my health cannot be ever satisfactory or even tolerable.</p>
      <p>I perceive that the scientific &amp; sedentary line are (at any rate for the present) quite pernicious &amp; against the grain; but, were I a perfect Artiste, my opinion is that I should then need the scientific very probably. There seems to be a vast mass of useless &amp; irritating powers of confusion which long to have full scope in active &amp; artificial manufacturing such as neither the ordinary</p>
      <p>active pursuits or duties of life, nor the literary line of expression, can give vent to.</p>
      <p>Dr Locock said to me the other day: "The fact is that what "ought to be in you "local &amp; concentrated; "what is so in every other "woman I ever knew; is "all over your system; &amp; "the results are very "singular altogether, &amp; "make you require very</p>
      <p>"peculiar &amp; artificial "excitements, as a matter "of safety even for your "life &amp; happiness."--</p>
      <p>Altogether everything seems now doing well; owing to our various measures &amp; plans, &amp; I have good hope for the future; better than I have yet had, on the whole I think.--</p>
      <p>Dear Mate, I consult you on all my plans; but perhaps you will</p>
      <p>scarcely comprehend my meaning &amp; ideas altogether; tho' I do hope you will; for your approbation &amp; aid is more necessary to me than anything; or at least a very necessary adjunct.--</p>
      <p>Believe that my present plans about myself &amp; my occupations, are altered, not from versatility or caprice; but from a deep study of</p>
      <p>that which is necessary &amp; advisable for me.</p>
      <p>And believe also, that Music &amp; the Drama, studied as I mean to study them, are far from being superficial, frivolous, or each wholly unconnected with the Scientific.--</p>
      <p>The effects of singing upon me are very curious physically. My longing to begin singing must have been a happy instinct.--</p>
    </div></body>
